    "recap_headline": "University of Massachusets Athletics",
    "recap_text": "AKRON, Ohio -\nUniversity of Massachusetts baseball edged out Akron, 5-4, on Saturday afternoon at Skeeles Field to earn its first Mid-American Conference win of the season.\nUMass improved to 5-6 overall on the season and 1-4 in the MAC, while Akron moved to 8-10 overall and 2-3 in the league.\nGavin O'Brien\nwent 2-for-3 on the afternoon, including a double and a home run, while adding a team-best two RBI and a run.\nAnthony Tirado\nand\nTy Fox\nfollowed with one hit each, as Tirado recorded his first homer of the season and Fox had his second triple of the year. Tirado led the team with two runs and had an RBI, along with Fox and\nJack Beverly\n.\nThe Minutemen pulled ahead early, scoring four in the top of the opening frame. Tirado led off the inning with a double to left field, followed by a triple from Fox to score Tirado and make it a 1-0 game. Beverly hit a grounder to second base that allowed Fox to cross the plate to lead 2-0. After\nReece McCarthy\nadvanced to third on an error, O'Brien recorded his third home run of the season to knock in two runs to give UMass a 4-0 lead.\nAkron scored two runs in the bottom half of the first, as UMass maintained a 4-2 lead. The Zips added another run in the third with Massachusetts holding a 4-3 lead.\nWith one out in the top of the fifth, Tirado blasted a solo shot over the right field fence to extend Massachusetts' lead to 5-3. It marked Tirado's first homer of the year and fifth of his career.\nAkron scored another run to keep it a close 5-4 game in the bottom half of the fifth.\nBoth teams held strong on defense for the final four frames, as the Minutemen ended the bottom of the ninth with a double play to save the run at home. The saved run gave UMass the 5-4 victory.\nGavin Sitarz\n(1-0) received the win for Massachusetts, allowing no runs, one hit, walking two and striking out one in two complete innings pitched. It marked Sitarz's first collegiate win.\nJack Niedringhaus\nearned his second save of the year after giving up one hit with no runs, a walk and dealing one strikeout in an inning of work.\nElijah Griffith (2-1) took the loss for Akron, allowing five runs on four hits, a walk and striking out four in five complete innings.\nUMass and Akron set for the rubber match on Sunday, March 15, at Skeeles Field in Akron, Ohio. First pitch is slated for a 12 p.m. start."
